========== WHAT DIDN'T VERIFY (and why) ==========
Full train_clm.hexa run on pod stalled at 100% CPU, 1.4GB RAM after 72s
with zero output produced. No syntax error, no segfault — the interpreter
is simply too slow to complete the file's self-tests (decoder_forward +
3× train_step at d=16) in under a minute. RAM growth is linear with
module-level tensor primitive setup.

This matches the pre-existing note in training/model_1b_gpu.hexa:
  "interpreter-limited (from R8 training step): >100× slower until codegen"

This is NOT a scale_1_5b port defect — the same file without our edit
exhibits the same behavior (the self-tests were written for eventual
codegen, not interpreter evaluation).

========== HEXA RUNTIME LIMITATIONS HIT ==========
1. No linux pre-built binary in GitHub release assets (Darwin arm64 only).
   Fresh pods require self-built toolchain (manual flatten + gcc).
2. Interpreter perf: a 2500-LOC hexa file with O(N²D) tensor primitives
   in _block_attn / decoder_backward self-tests takes >>60s per forward
   pass even at d=16 — full run likely >10min.
3. @link("/absolute/path/*.dylib") hardcoded to Mac paths. On Linux
   the .dylib files don't exist; FFI-dependent code paths (BLAS
   hxlmhead_bwd / hxblas_sgemm) would dlopen-fail at first call. For
   real training on linux, a parallel @link(".../libhxblas.so") guard
   or a build-time path substitution is needed.

========== .PY → .HEXA REPLACEMENT FEASIBILITY ==========
Short answer: NOT YET for the full train loop.

The structural port (scale config, phase manager, checkpoint policy,
eval struct) is already done and verified — our edit extends that.

The blocking gap is the TRAIN LOOP IMPLEMENTATION:
- train_clm.hexa's train_step uses @link .dylib for LM head backward
  (hxlmhead_bwd FFI). This is the hot path — works on Mac, needs Linux
  .so rebuild + path guard.
- torch.compile equivalent (SM90 tensor core codegen) doesn't exist in
  hexa yet. Without it, ~410 ms/step estimate from clm_1b_config.json
  becomes >>40s/step in the interpreter — 100× slowdown matches the
  model_1b_gpu.hexa commentary.
- Corpus loader (load_corpus), optimizer step (AdamW), DataLoader, and
  torch.save/load are all TODO[pytorch] stubs in the current .hexa.

Bottom line: train_clm.hexa scale_1_5b() is ready for when the rest of
the train loop lands (hxcuda kernels + linux .so FFI + corpus I/O).
Until then, train_clm_1b.py remains the operational training entry
point for 1.5B scale runs.

========== TOP 3 BLOCKERS ==========
1. Hexa codegen → native binary path for decoder_forward/backward +
   AdamW step. Interpreter is 100× too slow to even benchmark.
2. Linux .so FFI builds for hxblas / hxlmhead / hxcuda + path guard
   in @link attributes (Mac-only right now).
3. hexa corpus loader + torch.save replacement — need binary-format
   checkpoint primitive matching the pre-save rotation rules.

